Video Game Clustering Project

Unsupervised Learning Framework for Game Archetype Segmentation

Project Goal

Automatically segment video games into distinct archetypes (e.g., "Critically Acclaimed Blockbusters", "Underrated Gems") by analyzing patterns between commercial performance and critical reception.

Dataset

Kaggle Video Game Sales with Ratings: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/rush4ratio/video-game-sales-with-ratings/data

# convert non-numeric values in User_Score to NaN
df_relevant['User_Score'] = pd.to_numeric(df_relevant['User_Score'], errors='coerce')

# remove games with very low review counts cause scores from tiny samples are unreliable

In[14]:
# Find best min_samples and eps using grid search with silhouette score
min_samples_range = range(3, 5)
epsilon_range = np.arange(1.2299, 1.2301, 0.01) # change both to 0.3, 2 later
results = []

for ms in min_samples_range:
    for ep in epsilon_range:
        labels = DBSCAN(min_samples=ms, eps=ep).fit(X_reduced).labels_
        
        # only compute silhouette if we have actual clusters (not just noise)
        if len(set(labels)) > 1 and -1 not in labels or (len(set(labels)) > 2 and -1 in labels):
            score = silhouette_score(X_reduced, labels)
            results.append((ms, ep, score))

if results:
    best_min_samples, best_eps, best_score = sorted(results, key=lambda x: x[-1])[-1]
    print(f"Best silhouette score: {best_score:.4f}")
    print(f"Best min_samples: {best_min_samples}")
    print(f"Best eps: {best_eps:.4f}")
else:
    print("No valid clusters found in search range")

Best silhouette score: 0.7660
Best min_samples: 4
Best eps: 1.2299

In[17]:
# Compute metrics for KMeans
sil_kmeans = silhouette_score(X_reduced, y_kmeans)
db_kmeans = davies_bouldin_score(X_reduced, y_kmeans)
ch_kmeans = calinski_harabasz_score(X_reduced, y_kmeans)

# Compute metrics for Hierarchical
sil_hierarchical = silhouette_score(X_reduced, y_hierarchical)
db_hierarchical = davies_bouldin_score(X_reduced, y_hierarchical)
ch_hierarchical = calinski_harabasz_score(X_reduced, y_hierarchical)

# Compute metrics for DBSCAN (exclude noise labeled as -1)
mask_dbscan = y_dbscan != -1
sil_dbscan = silhouette_score(X_reduced[mask_dbscan], y_dbscan[mask_dbscan])
db_dbscan = davies_bouldin_score(X_reduced[mask_dbscan], y_dbscan[mask_dbscan])
ch_dbscan = calinski_harabasz_score(X_reduced[mask_dbscan], y_dbscan[mask_dbscan])

# Create comparison table
comparison_df = pd.DataFrame({
    'Model': ['KMeans', 'DBSCAN', 'Hierarchical'],
    'Silhouette': [sil_kmeans, sil_dbscan, sil_hierarchical],
    'Davies-Bouldin': [db_kmeans, db_dbscan, db_hierarchical],
    'Calinski-Harabasz': [ch_kmeans, ch_dbscan, ch_hierarchical]
})

print("Model Comparison:")
print("Higher Silhouette & Calinski-Harabasz = better")
print("Lower Davies-Bouldin = better")
display(comparison_df)

Final Analysis & Conclusion

Cluster 0 "Critically Acclaimed High Performers"

Profile: High commercial success (1316M sales) with strong critical praise (critic scores 7795, avg 87.4). User scores show more variability (5.38.7), indicating critic-player disagreement in some cases (e.g., Call of Duty: Black Ops II). Sales heavily weighted toward North America and Europe, with minimal Japan sales except Brain Age 2 (5.32M JP). Includes Western AAA titles (GTA, CoD, Gran Turismo) and occasional Japanese hits with global appeal.

Archetype Label: "Critic-Approved Blockbusters"

Traditional "prestige" tierhigh budget, high review scores, strong market performance, but not always universal user adoration.

Cluster 1 "Commercial & Critical Underperformers"

Profile: Low sales (24M), poor critic scores (2563), and low user scores (<6.0). All titles are casual/sports/minigame compilations for Wii (Carnival Games, Wii Music, Cooking Mama, Deca Sports, Game Party). Limited attention from both critics and players (low review counts). Sales concentrated in North America and Europe, negligible Japanese sales. Aimed at Western casual market but failed to achieve critical respect or commercial success.

Archetype Label: "Casual-Market Flops"

Lower end of the quality-commercial spectrumlow-investment, low-return products in the long tail.

Cluster 2 "Mass-Market User Favorites"

Profile: Highest-selling games (2982M sales) with very high user scores (avg 7.88, mostly >8.0) but solid, non-elite critic scores (avg 77.0). Wii Play scored only 58 yet sold 29M copies, showing mass-market appeal can outweigh critical reception. Enormous sales across all regions, particularly North America and Europe, with significant Japanese sales (e.g., New Super Mario Bros. 6.5M JP). All Nintendo first-party or bundled Wii/DS software targeting families and casual gamers.

Archetype Label: "User-Adored Blockbusters"

Cultural touchstones driven by word-of-mouth, brand recognition, and accessible gameplaypinnacle of commercial achievement and user satisfaction.

Conclusion:

Unsupervised segmentation successfully uncovered three distinct video game archetypes defined by the interplay between commercial success and critical reception:

  • "Critic-Approved Blockbusters" (Cluster 0): Strong sales through high critic scores, despite occasional user-critic disagreement
  • "Casual-Market Flops" (Cluster 1): Poor reviews, low engagement, and modest sales
  • "User-Adored Blockbusters" (Cluster 2): Exceptional sales driven by positive player reception, even with average critic scores

Key Findings: High critic scores don't guarantee universal user approval or massive commercial success. User satisfaction can independently propel games to cultural phenomenon status. The gaming market is not monolithic"worthwhile" games can be defined by either critical prestige or grassroots player adoration.

Project Impact: The unsupervised approach recovered these meaningful groupings from raw metadata without prior labeling, validating its value for automatically estimating a game's market positioning and quality profile. This framework provides a scalable method for discovering latent structures in large-scale game datasets.
